Note: ============================================================================
Note: Semantic Analyzer Structures
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Haskell semantic analysis needs five orthogonal environments
(symbols, types, classes, instances, modules) plus a constraint
solver and error/warning collectors. Keeping them as separate
hashtables means each lookup is O(1) and the phases of analysis
(name resolution, type inference, class resolution) can each
target the relevant store without iterating noise.
current_scope tracks lexical depth; type_var_counter generates
fresh type variables for the Hindley-Milner pass.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
80-byte record (10 fields × 8 bytes):
- symbol_table @0 - global symbol map (HashTable)
- type_env @8 - type name -> HaskellType (HashTable)
- class_env @16 - type class name -> class id (HashTable)
- instance_env @24 - instance map (HashTable)
- module_env @32 - module name -> declarations (HashTable)
- scope_stack @40 - List of per-scope name frames (lexical scope tracking)
- error_list @48 - List of error strings
- warning_list @56 - List of warning strings
- current_scope @64 - integer depth (entered/exited per scope)
- type_var_counter @72 - monotonic counter for fresh tN names
@End Implementation
Type called "HaskellSemanticAnalyzer":
    symbol_table as Integer         Note: Global symbol table
    type_env as Integer             Note: Type environment
    class_env as Integer            Note: Type class environment
    instance_env as Integer         Note: Instance environment
    module_env as Integer           Note: Module environment
    constraint_solver as Integer    Note: Type constraint solver
    error_list as Integer           Note: List of semantic errors
    warning_list as Integer         Note: List of warnings
    current_scope as Integer        Note: Current scope level
    type_var_counter as Integer     Note: Counter for fresh type variables
End Type

@Reasoning:
Compact representation of a Haskell type that can model any of
the surface forms (basic, variable, function, list, tuple, etc.)
via the constructor tag. The parameters list lets one shape model
both unary (list, Maybe) and n-ary (function, tuple) types; the
substitution slot caches the resolved binding for type variables
during unification.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
40-byte record (5 fields × 8 bytes):
- kind @0 - one of KIND_STAR / KIND_ARROW / KIND_CONSTRAINT
- constructor @8 - either a TYPE_* constant (for concrete types)
  or a string pointer (for type variables - the variable name)
- parameters @16 - List of nested HaskellType pointers
- constraints @24 - List of attached type class constraints
- substitution @32 - bound HaskellType after unification
@End Implementation
Type called "HaskellType":
    kind as Integer                 Note: Type kind
    constructor as Integer          Note: Type constructor name
    parameters as Integer           Note: Type parameters (list)
    constraints as Integer          Note: Type class constraints
    substitution as Integer         Note: Type variable substitution
End Type

@Reasoning:
A type scheme `forall a b. (C a) => T a b` separates universally
quantified variables from the underlying type. Instantiation
replaces the bound variables with fresh ones so each use of a
polymorphic value gets its own copy of the variables.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
24-byte record:
- quantified_vars @0 - List of bound variable name strings
- constraints @8 - List of type class constraints
- type @16 - the underlying HaskellType being quantified
@End Implementation
Type called "HaskellTypeScheme":
    quantified_vars as Integer      Note: Universally quantified variables
    constraints as Integer          Note: Type class constraints
    type as Integer                 Note: The actual type
End Type

@Reasoning:
Type class constraint records "T must implement Class". Carries
source location so error messages can point to the originating
expression rather than just listing the unsatisfied constraint.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
24-byte record:
- class_name @0 - integer id of the type class (TYPECLASS_*)
- type_arg @8 - HaskellType the class is applied to
- source_location @16 - source coordinates (0 if synthesized)
@End Implementation
Type called "HaskellConstraint":
    class_name as Integer           Note: Type class name
    type_arg as Integer             Note: Type argument
    source_location as Integer      Note: Where constraint originated
End Type

@Reasoning:
Symbol table entry. Includes both the type scheme and metadata
(definition location, scope level, constructor flag, arity) so
later lookups can answer "what type, defined where, what scope"
without walking the AST.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
48-byte record (6 fields × 8 bytes):
- name @0 - identifier string
- type_scheme @8 - HaskellTypeScheme pointer
- definition_location @16 - source coords
- scope_level @24 - integer scope at definition time
- is_constructor @32 - 0 for variables, 1 for data constructors
- arity @40 - constructor arity (0 for non-constructors)
@End Implementation
Type called "HaskellSymbol":
    name as Integer                 Note: Symbol name
    type_scheme as Integer          Note: Type scheme
    definition_location as Integer  Note: Where symbol is defined
    scope_level as Integer          Note: Scope level
    is_constructor as Integer       Note: Is data constructor
    arity as Integer                Note: Constructor arity
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Semantic Analyzer Creation and Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The analyzer state needs five independent name-resolution scopes
(symbol, type, class, instance, module) plus error and warning
collections. Splitting them into separate hashtables (rather than a
single union table) lets type-vs-class disambiguation happen by
table membership instead of by string prefix - critical for getting
Haskell's separate namespace semantics right.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates an 80-byte analyzer (10 i64 slots), returns 0 on failure.
Initialises slot layout: symbol_table @0, type_env @8, class_env @16,
instance_env @24, module_env @32 (all fresh hashtables);
constraint_solver @40 (zeroed); errors @48, warnings @56 (fresh
Lists); current_scope @64 = 0; type_var_counter @72 = 0. After
zeroing, calls populate_builtin_environment to seed the Prelude
types and classes so user code can reference Int, Maybe, Eq, etc.
without explicit imports.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_haskell_semantic_analyzer" returns Integer:
    Let analyzer_size be 80  Note: 10 fields × 8 bytes each
    Let analyzer be proc allocate from Layout with analyzer_size

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize symbol table
    Let symbol_table be proc hashtable_create from HashTable
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0, symbol_table

    Note: Initialize type environment
    Let type_env be proc hashtable_create from HashTable
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8, type_env

    Note: Initialize class environment
    Let class_env be proc hashtable_create from HashTable
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16, class_env

    Note: Initialize instance environment
    Let instance_env be proc hashtable_create from HashTable
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24, instance_env

    Note: Initialize module environment
    Let module_env be proc hashtable_create from HashTable
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32, module_env

    Note: Initialize lexical-scope frame stack (offset 40). Each frame is a
    Note: List of the variable names bound at that scope level, so exiting a
    Note: scope can delete exactly those bindings from the symbol table.
    Let scope_stack be proc list_create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40, scope_stack

    Note: Initialize error and warning lists
    Let error_list be proc list_create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48, error_list

    Let warning_list be proc list_create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56, warning_list

    Note: Initialize scope and type variable counter
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64, 0  Note: current_scope
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72, 0  Note: type_var_counter

    Note: Populate with built-in types and classes
    proc populate_builtin_environment with analyzer

    Return analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Releases every owned heap resource: five hashtables (symbol,
type, class, instance, module), and two lists (errors, warnings).
The constraint_solver slot is currently unused so it has no
dedicated destroy call. Idempotent on a null analyzer pointer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 if analyzer is 0. For each of the five hashtables
(offsets 0, 8, 16, 24, 32) reads the pointer; if non-zero calls
hashtable_destroy. For each of the two lists (offsets 48, 56)
reads and calls list_destroy. Deallocates the analyzer record.
Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "destroy_haskell_semantic_analyzer" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy semantic analyzer and free all memory

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Destroy symbol table
    Let symbol_table be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    If symbol_table is not equal to 0:
        proc hashtable_destroy from HashTable with symbol_table
    End If

    Note: Destroy type environment
    Let type_env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    If type_env is not equal to 0:
        proc hashtable_destroy from HashTable with type_env
    End If

    Note: Destroy class environment
    Let class_env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16
    If class_env is not equal to 0:
        proc hashtable_destroy from HashTable with class_env
    End If

    Note: Destroy instance environment
    Let instance_env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24
    If instance_env is not equal to 0:
        proc hashtable_destroy from HashTable with instance_env
    End If

    Note: Destroy module environment
    Let module_env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32
    If module_env is not equal to 0:
        proc hashtable_destroy from HashTable with module_env
    End If

    Note: Destroy the lexical-scope frame stack and each remaining frame list
    Let scope_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40
    If scope_stack is not equal to 0:
        Let frame_count be proc list_length from List with scope_stack
        Let frame_idx be 0
        While frame_idx is less than frame_count:
            Let frame be proc list_get from List with scope_stack, frame_idx
            If frame is not equal to 0:
                proc list_destroy from List with frame
            End If
            Set frame_idx to frame_idx plus 1
        End While
        proc list_destroy from List with scope_stack
    End If

    Note: Destroy error list
    Let error_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    If error_list is not equal to 0:
        proc list_destroy from List with error_list
    End If

    Note: Destroy warning list
    Let warning_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56
    If warning_list is not equal to 0:
        proc list_destroy from List with warning_list
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with analyzer
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Pre-loads every Prelude name a Haskell module can use without an
explicit import. Splitting types vs classes vs operators vs functions
into separate add_* calls (rather than one giant loop) keeps each
section self-documenting and lets the type/class IDs be the
authoritative source of truth referenced by lookup_basic_type.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads type_env @8 and class_env @16. Calls add_builtin_type for the
six primitive types (Int, Float, Double, Char, Bool, String) and the
compound types (Maybe, Either, IO). Then adds the Prelude classes
(Eq, Ord, Show, Read, Num, Functor, Monad, ...). Symbol-level Prelude
functions (length, map, ...) are also seeded with their type schemes
so resolution succeeds without explicit imports.
@End Implementation
Process called "populate_builtin_environment" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Let type_env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let class_env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16

    Note: Add primitive types
    proc add_builtin_type with analyzer, "Int", TYPE_INT
    proc add_builtin_type with analyzer, "Float", TYPE_FLOAT
    proc add_builtin_type with analyzer, "Double", TYPE_FLOAT
    proc add_builtin_type with analyzer, "Char", TYPE_CHAR
    proc add_builtin_type with analyzer, "Bool", TYPE_BOOL
    proc add_builtin_type with analyzer, "String", TYPE_STRING

    Note: Add compound types
    proc add_builtin_type with analyzer, "Maybe", TYPE_MAYBE
    proc add_builtin_type with analyzer, "Either", TYPE_EITHER
    proc add_builtin_type with analyzer, "IO", TYPE_IO

    Note: Add type classes
    proc add_builtin_class with analyzer, "Eq", TYPECLASS_EQ
    proc add_builtin_class with analyzer, "Ord", TYPECLASS_ORD
    proc add_builtin_class with analyzer, "Show", TYPECLASS_SHOW
    proc add_builtin_class with analyzer, "Read", TYPECLASS_READ
    proc add_builtin_class with analyzer, "Enum", TYPECLASS_ENUM
    proc add_builtin_class with analyzer, "Bounded", TYPECLASS_BOUNDED
    proc add_builtin_class with analyzer, "Num", TYPECLASS_NUM
    proc add_builtin_class with analyzer, "Real", TYPECLASS_REAL
    proc add_builtin_class with analyzer, "Integral", TYPECLASS_INTEGRAL
    proc add_builtin_class with analyzer, "Fractional", TYPECLASS_FRACTIONAL
    proc add_builtin_class with analyzer, "Floating", TYPECLASS_FLOATING
    proc add_builtin_class with analyzer, "Functor", TYPECLASS_FUNCTOR
    proc add_builtin_class with analyzer, "Applicative", TYPECLASS_APPLICATIVE
    proc add_builtin_class with analyzer, "Monad", TYPECLASS_MONAD

    Note: Add built-in functions
    proc add_builtin_function with analyzer, "id", "a -> a"
    proc add_builtin_function with analyzer, "const", "a -> b -> a"
    proc add_builtin_function with analyzer, "fst", "(a, b) -> a"
    proc add_builtin_function with analyzer, "snd", "(a, b) -> b"
    proc add_builtin_function with analyzer, "head", "[a] -> a"
    proc add_builtin_function with analyzer, "tail", "[a] -> [a]"
    proc add_builtin_function with analyzer, "null", "[a] -> Bool"
    proc add_builtin_function with analyzer, "length", "[a] -> Int"
    proc add_builtin_function with analyzer, "map", "(a -> b) -> [a] -> [b]"
    proc add_builtin_function with analyzer, "filter", "(a -> Bool) -> [a] -> [a]"
    proc add_builtin_function with analyzer, "foldr", "(a -> b -> b) -> b -> [a] -> b"
    proc add_builtin_function with analyzer, "foldl", "(b -> a -> b) -> b -> [a] -> b"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers a Prelude type (Int, Float, Bool, etc.) into the type
environment. Allocates a fresh string copy of the name (rather
than aliasing) so the hashtable owns its keys and the caller can
free the original string.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads type_env (analyzer offset 8). Copies name via
StringCore.create_string. Builds a HaskellType via
create_haskell_type with the supplied type_id as constructor.
Inserts into type_env keyed by the new name string.
@End Implementation
Process called "add_builtin_type" takes analyzer as Integer, name as Integer, type_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add built-in type to type environment

    Let type_env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let type_name_str be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with name

    Note: Create type representation
    Let type_obj be proc create_haskell_type with type_id
    proc hashtable_set from HashTable with type_env, type_name_str, type_obj

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers a Prelude type class (Eq, Ord, Show, Num, etc.) into
class_env keyed by name. Stores the class id directly (no extra
record allocation) - the class id is the integer enum used by
constraints.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads class_env (analyzer offset 16). Copies name via
StringCore.create_string. Inserts class_id (an integer) under the
copied name into class_env.
@End Implementation
Process called "add_builtin_class" takes analyzer as Integer, name as Integer, class_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add built-in type class to class environment

    Let class_env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16
    Let class_name_str be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with name

    Note: Create class representation
    proc hashtable_set from HashTable with class_env, class_name_str, class_id

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers a Prelude function ("id", "head", "map", ...) by
parsing its textual type signature into a type scheme and binding
it into the symbol table. The signature parser handles function,
list, and tuple shapes plus type variables so the resulting
scheme is fully polymorphic where the source signature is.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads symbol_table (analyzer offset 0). Copies name via
StringCore.create_string. Parses type_str via parse_type_signature
into a type scheme pointer. Inserts the scheme under the name
into symbol_table.
@End Implementation
Process called "add_builtin_function" takes analyzer as Integer, name as Integer, type_str as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add built-in function to symbol table

    Let symbol_table be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    Let func_name_str be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with name

    Note: Parse type string and create type scheme
    Let type_scheme be proc parse_type_signature with type_str
    proc hashtable_set from HashTable with symbol_table, func_name_str, type_scheme

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Type System Operations
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Every Haskell type object carries five orthogonal pieces of state:
kind (* by default - all monomorphic types have kind *), constructor
(which named type or variable this is), parameters (type arguments
for higher-kinded use), constraints (class constraints from "C a =>
..."), and substitution (current binding during unification). The
default kind is * because most types created here are monomorphic;
the kind is upgraded by the caller for higher-kinded types.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 40 bytes (5 i64 slots), returns 0 on failure. Initialises
slot layout: kind @0 = KIND_STAR, type_constructor @8 (parameter),
parameters @16 = 0, constraints @24 = 0, substitution @32 = 0. The
zero-init for parameters/constraints/substitution lets callers fill
those slots only when needed.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_haskell_type" takes type_constructor as Integer returns Integer:
    Let type_size be 40  Note: 5 fields × 8 bytes each
    Let type_obj be proc allocate from Layout with type_size

    If type_obj is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with type_obj, 0, KIND_STAR  Note: Default kind
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with type_obj, 8, type_constructor
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with type_obj, 16, 0  Note: parameters
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with type_obj, 24, 0  Note: constraints
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with type_obj, 32, 0  Note: substitution

    Return type_obj
End Process

@Reasoning:
The Hindley-Milner algorithm needs an unbounded supply of fresh type
variables that are guaranteed distinct from any existing variable.
The analyzer holds a monotonic counter (offset 72) that is bumped
on each call - the per-analyzer scope guarantees uniqueness across
the entire inference run.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads counter @72, increments, writes back. Calls create_type_var_name
with the new counter value to produce a variable name like "t1", "t2".
Calls create_haskell_type with TYPE_VARIABLE as the constructor.
Writes the variable name into the type's constructor slot at offset 8
(this offset doubles as the variable-name slot for TYPE_VARIABLE
type-objects). Returns the type object.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_fresh_type_variable" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Let counter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72
    Set counter to counter plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72, counter

    Note: Create type variable name like "t1", "t2", etc.
    Let var_name be proc create_type_var_name with counter
    Let type_var be proc create_haskell_type with TYPE_VARIABLE

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with type_var, 8, var_name

    Return type_var
End Process

@Reasoning:
Generates names like "t1", "t2", "t3" for fresh type variables.
Using a counter avoids any chance of collision with user-written
type variable names (which are lowercase and start with a letter
that isn't 't' followed by digits, by convention).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates the string "t" via StringCore.create_string. Converts
the integer counter to its decimal-string representation via
StringCore.int_to_string. Concatenates the two with
StringCore.string_concat to form the variable name. Deallocates
the two intermediate strings (the concatenated result is the
return value).
@End Implementation
@Reasoning:
StringCore offers no whitespace-trim primitive, so the type-signature
parser carries its own. Trimming leading/trailing ASCII spaces and tabs
is all the Haskell type-string scanner needs (newlines never appear in a
single type token at this stage).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Scans from both ends past bytes 32 (space) and 9 (tab) to compute the
trimmed [first, last] inclusive range, then copies that range into a
freshly owned-heap NUL-terminated buffer via StringPrim.string_substring
(start = first, length = last - first + 1). An all-whitespace or empty
input yields a freshly allocated empty string so callers can always
deallocate the result uniformly.
@End Implementation
Process called "haskell_trim" takes str as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Return a new string with leading/trailing spaces and tabs removed

    If str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let str_len be proc string_length from StringCore with str
    Let first be 0
    While first is less than str_len:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with str, first
        If ch is equal to 32:
            Set first to first plus 1
        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 9:
                Set first to first plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Let last be str_len minus 1
    While last is greater than or equal to first:
        Let tail_ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with str, last
        If tail_ch is equal to 32:
            Set last to last minus 1
        Otherwise:
            If tail_ch is equal to 9:
                Set last to last minus 1
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If
    End While

    If last is less than first:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with ""
    End If

    Let trimmed_length be last minus first plus 1
    Return proc string_substring from StringPrim with str, first, trimmed_length
End Process

@Reasoning:
Numeric-literal classification needs a contains-character test that
StringCore does not provide; this self-contained scan mirrors the lexer's
equivalent helper so the semantic pass can decide int vs float from a
literal string.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Walks indices 0..length-1, returning 1 on the first byte equal to
target_char and 0 otherwise (including null/empty input).
@End Implementation
Process called "haskell_contains_char" takes str as Integer, target_char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Return 1 if str contains target_char, else 0

    If str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let scan_len be proc string_length from StringCore with str
    Let idx be 0
    While idx is less than scan_len:
        Let scan_ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with str, idx
        If scan_ch is equal to target_char:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set idx to idx plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "create_type_var_name" takes counter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create type variable name from counter

    Let prefix be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "t"
    Let counter_str be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with counter
    Let var_name be proc string_concat from StringPrim with prefix, counter_str

    proc deallocate from Layout with counter_str

    Return var_name
End Process

@Reasoning:
The Robinson unification algorithm specialised for Haskell's type
language. Branches on constructor identity to dispatch to the
correct sub-routine (variable, function, list, tuple). The
constructor-equality fast path handles the common case (Int vs Int,
Maybe vs Maybe) without descending into the per-shape routines.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 on either null. Reads constructor1 / constructor2 (offset
8 of each type object). If equal, recurses on parameter lists
(offset 16) via unify_type_parameters. If either is TYPE_VARIABLE,
delegates to unify_variable (which performs the occurs check). Same-
shape branches: TYPE_FUNCTION -> unify_function_types,
TYPE_LIST -> unify_list_types, TYPE_TUPLE -> unify_tuple_types. On
mismatch, records "Cannot unify types" via add_type_error and
returns 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "unify_types" takes analyzer as Integer, type1 as Integer, type2 as Integer returns Integer:
    If type1 is equal to 0 or type2 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let constructor1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type1, 8
    Let constructor2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type2, 8

    Note: Same type constructor
    If constructor1 is equal to constructor2:
        Note: Unify parameters
        Let params1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type1, 16
        Let params2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type2, 16

        Return proc unify_type_parameters with analyzer, params1, params2
    End If

    Note: Type variable unification
    If constructor1 is equal to TYPE_VARIABLE:
        Return proc unify_variable with analyzer, type1, type2
    End If

    If constructor2 is equal to TYPE_VARIABLE:
        Return proc unify_variable with analyzer, type2, type1
    End If

    Note: Function type unification
    If constructor1 is equal to TYPE_FUNCTION and constructor2 is equal to TYPE_FUNCTION:
        Return proc unify_function_types with analyzer, type1, type2
    End If

    Note: List type unification
    If constructor1 is equal to TYPE_LIST and constructor2 is equal to TYPE_LIST:
        Return proc unify_list_types with analyzer, type1, type2
    End If

    Note: Tuple type unification
    If constructor1 is equal to TYPE_TUPLE and constructor2 is equal to TYPE_TUPLE:
        Return proc unify_tuple_types with analyzer, type1, type2
    End If

    Note: Types cannot be unified
    proc add_type_error with analyzer, "Cannot unify types"
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Binding a type variable to a type is the most common substitution
created during inference. The occurs check is a soundness requirement:
without it, "a = [a]" would succeed and produce an infinite type.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads var_name from offset 8 of var_type. Calls occurs_check on
var_name vs other_type. On occurs == 1, records "Occurs check
failed - infinite type" and returns 0. Otherwise creates and returns
a substitution {var_name -> other_type} via create_substitution.
@End Implementation
Process called "unify_variable" takes analyzer as Integer, var_type as Integer, other_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Let var_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with var_type, 8

    Note: Occurs check - prevent infinite types
    Let occurs be proc occurs_check with var_name, other_type
    If occurs is equal to 1:
        proc add_type_error with analyzer, "Occurs check failed - infinite type"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create substitution
    Let substitution be proc create_substitution with var_name, other_type
    Return substitution
End Process

@Reasoning:
The occurs check is one of the two halves of Hindley-Milner that
guarantee termination - without it, unification could loop forever
on cyclic types. This routine recursively walks the type structure
looking for the variable name; returns 1 (occurs) as soon as one
is found, short-circuiting the rest of the walk.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 on null type. Reads constructor at offset 8. If
TYPE_VARIABLE, compares the other type's var name (also at offset 8)
to var_name via string_equals; returns 1 if equal, 0 otherwise. For
all other constructors, reads parameters list (offset 16) and
delegates to occurs_check_in_list to recurse on each sub-type.
Returns 0 if the type has no parameters.
@End Implementation
Process called "occurs_check" takes var_name as Integer, type_expr as Integer returns Integer:
    If type_expr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let constructor be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_expr, 8

    Note: If this is the same variable
    If constructor is equal to TYPE_VARIABLE:
        Let other_var_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_expr, 8
        Let is_same be proc string_equals from StringCore with var_name, other_var_name
        If is_same is equal to 1:
            Return 1  Note: Variable occurs
        End If
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check in type parameters
    Let parameters be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_expr, 16
    If parameters is not equal to 0:
        Return proc occurs_check_in_list with var_name, parameters
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Helper for occurs_check: when a type has parameters (a list of
sub-types), this routine checks each parameter recursively for
the variable's presence. The occurs check is what prevents
Hindley-Milner from constructing infinite types like a = [a] - a
fundamental soundness requirement.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 if type_list is 0 (empty). Reads list_length via
List.get_length. Iterates i = 0..list_length-1: reads each
current_type via List.get, recursively calls occurs_check with
var_name and current_type. Returns 1 immediately on the first
occurrence. Returns 0 after exhausting the list.
@End Implementation
Process called "occurs_check_in_list" takes var_name as Integer, type_list as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if variable occurs in list of types

    If type_list is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Iterate through list and check each type for occurrence
    Let list_length be proc get_length from List with type_list

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than list_length:
        Let current_type be proc get from List with type_list, i

        Note: Recursively check if variable occurs in this type
        Let occurs be proc occurs_check with var_name, current_type

        If occurs is equal to 1:
            Note: Variable occurs in this type - fail occurs check
            Return 1
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Variable does not occur in any type in list
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Type Inference
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Dispatch table for Hindley-Milner type inference. Each AST expression
kind (literal, identifier, application, lambda, case, let, ...) has
its own inference rule. Centralising the dispatch here keeps the
type checker structurally identical to a Haskell-style "infer ::
Expr -> TyEnv -> Type" function and makes adding new expression
kinds a single new If branch.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads expression's kind field. Dispatches via If chain to:
infer_literal_type, infer_identifier_type, infer_application_type,
infer_lambda_type, infer_case_type, infer_list_type, infer_tuple_type,
infer_if_type, infer_let_type, infer_do_type. Returns the inferred
type or 0 on dispatch miss. The caller is responsible for adding any
discovered constraints to the analyzer.
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_expression_type" takes analyzer as Integer, expr as Integer returns Integer:
    If expr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let expr_type be proc get_haskell_ast_type from Parser with expr
    Let expr_value be proc get_haskell_ast_value from Parser with expr

    Note: Literal expressions
    If expr_type is equal to AST_LITERAL from Parser:
        Return proc infer_literal_type with analyzer, expr_value
    End If

    Note: Identifier expressions
    If expr_type is equal to AST_IDENTIFIER from Parser:
        Return proc infer_identifier_type with analyzer, expr_value
    End If

    Note: Function application
    If expr_type is equal to AST_APPLICATION from Parser:
        Return proc infer_application_type with analyzer, expr
    End If

    Note: Lambda expressions
    If expr_type is equal to AST_LAMBDA from Parser:
        Return proc infer_lambda_type with analyzer, expr
    End If

    Note: Let expressions
    If expr_type is equal to AST_LET from Parser:
        Return proc infer_let_type with analyzer, expr
    End If

    Note: Case expressions
    If expr_type is equal to AST_CASE from Parser:
        Return proc infer_case_type with analyzer, expr
    End If

    Note: If expressions
    If expr_type is equal to AST_IF from Parser:
        Return proc infer_if_type with analyzer, expr
    End If

    Note: List expressions
    If expr_type is equal to AST_LIST from Parser:
        Return proc infer_list_type with analyzer, expr
    End If

    Note: Tuple expressions
    If expr_type is equal to AST_TUPLE from Parser:
        Return proc infer_tuple_type with analyzer, expr
    End If

    Note: Do notation
    If expr_type is equal to AST_DO from Parser:
        Return proc infer_do_type with analyzer, expr
    End If

    Note: Unknown expression type
    proc add_type_error with analyzer, "Unknown expression type for inference"
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Classifies a literal by its lexeme prefix: ' starts Char, " starts
String, "True"/"False" identifies Bool, "." in the body distinguishes
Float from Int. Numeric literals are returned as polymorphic
TYPE_VARIABLE with a Num constraint - matching Haskell's actual
behaviour where "5" can typecheck as Int, Integer, Double, etc.
based on use site.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null literal returns TYPE_UNIT. Reads first character via
string_char_at. 39 (') -> TYPE_CHAR. 34 (") -> TYPE_STRING. Compares
against "True"/"False" via string_equals -> TYPE_BOOL. Otherwise
checks for "." (decimal point); present -> create_polymorphic_
numeric_type with TYPE_FLOAT, absent -> with TYPE_INT.
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_literal_type" takes analyzer as Integer, literal_value as Integer returns Integer:
    If literal_value is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_haskell_type with TYPE_UNIT
    End If

    Note: Determine literal type based on value format
    Let first_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with literal_value, 0

    Note: Character literal (starts with ')
    If first_char is equal to 39:  Note: '
        Return proc create_haskell_type with TYPE_CHAR
    End If

    Note: String literal (starts with ")
    If first_char is equal to 34:  Note: "
        Return proc create_haskell_type with TYPE_STRING
    End If

    Note: Boolean literals
    Let true_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "True"
    Let false_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "False"
    Let is_true be proc string_equals from StringCore with literal_value, true_str
    Let is_false be proc string_equals from StringCore with literal_value, false_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with true_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with false_str

    If is_true is equal to 1 or is_false is equal to 1:
        Return proc create_haskell_type with TYPE_BOOL
    End If

    Note: Numeric literals
    Let has_dot be proc haskell_contains_char with literal_value, 46  Note: .
    If has_dot is equal to 1:
        Note: Floating point literal
        Return proc create_polymorphic_numeric_type with analyzer, TYPE_FLOAT
    Otherwise:
        Note: Integer literal
        Return proc create_polymorphic_numeric_type with analyzer, TYPE_INT
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
A Haskell numeric literal has type "Num a => a" - polymorphic across
any Num instance. The implementation creates a fresh type variable
and a Num constraint pinning that variable, deferring resolution to
the constraint solver at the use site (where context may pick Int,
Integer, Double, ...).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a fresh type variable via create_fresh_type_variable.
Builds a TYPECLASS_NUM constraint over that variable via
create_type_constraint. Registers the constraint with the analyzer
via add_type_constraint. Returns the variable - the constraint
travels separately via the analyzer's constraint slot.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_polymorphic_numeric_type" takes analyzer as Integer, base_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Let type_var be proc create_fresh_type_variable with analyzer
    Let num_constraint be proc create_type_constraint with TYPECLASS_NUM, type_var

    Note: Add constraint to constraint solver
    proc add_type_constraint with analyzer, num_constraint

    Return type_var
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier resolution + scheme instantiation. The scheme stored in
the symbol table is the universally-quantified type (e.g. "forall a.
a -> a" for id); each use site must instantiate the bound variables
with fresh ones so the same scheme can be specialised differently at
each call.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads symbol_table @0 from analyzer. Looks up identifier via
hashtable_get. On miss, records "Undefined identifier" via
add_type_error and returns 0. On hit, calls instantiate_type_scheme
which produces a fresh-variable substitution and applies it,
returning the instantiated type.
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_identifier_type" takes analyzer as Integer, identifier as Integer returns Integer:
    Let symbol_table be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    Let symbol_info be proc hashtable_get from HashTable with symbol_table, identifier

    If symbol_info is equal to 0:
        Note: Undefined identifier
        proc add_type_error with analyzer, "Undefined identifier"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Instantiate type scheme with fresh type variables
    Return proc instantiate_type_scheme with analyzer, symbol_info
End Process

@Reasoning:
Hindley-Milner's let-polymorphism rule requires that every use of a
generalised type generate fresh type variables for the bound ones.
This routine implements that "instantiate" half of generalise/
instantiate by building a substitution from forall-bound variables
to fresh variables, then applying it to the underlying type.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 on null scheme. Reads bound_vars list @8 and bound_count
@16 from the scheme. Creates an empty substitution Dictionary.
Iterates bound_vars: for each bound_var, allocates a fresh_var via
create_fresh_type_variable, stores {bound_var -> fresh_var} in the
substitution. Reads the underlying type @24 from the scheme. Calls
apply_type_substitution to walk the type substituting bound for
fresh. Returns the instantiated type.
@End Implementation
Process called "instantiate_type_scheme" takes analyzer as Integer, type_scheme as Integer returns Integer:
    If type_scheme is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Instantiate quantified type variables with fresh type variables
    Note: Get forall-bound variables from type scheme (offset 8)
    Let bound_vars be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_scheme, 8
    Let bound_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_scheme, 16

    Note: Create substitution map for instantiation. The substitution is a
    Note: HashTable keyed by the bound variable's NAME (string) so the shared
    Note: substitute_into_type walker can match a TYPE_VARIABLE by its name.
    Let substitution be proc hashtable_create from HashTable

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than bound_count:
        Let bound_var be proc list_get from List with bound_vars, i

        Note: Create fresh type variable for this bound variable
        Let fresh_var be proc create_fresh_type_variable with analyzer

        Note: A bound var may be stored either as a bare name string or as a
        Note: TYPE_VARIABLE type object; normalise to the name string for the key.
        Let bound_var_name be bound_var
        If bound_var is not equal to 0:
            Let bv_constructor be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with bound_var, 0
            If bv_constructor is equal to KIND_STAR:
                Set bound_var_name to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with bound_var, 8
            End If
        End If

        Note: Add to substitution map
        proc hashtable_set from HashTable with substitution, bound_var_name, fresh_var

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Get the underlying type (offset 24)
    Let underlying_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_scheme, 24

    Note: Apply substitution to underlying type
    Let instantiated_type be proc apply_type_substitution with substitution, underlying_type

    Return instantiated_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Application inference uses the "expected" technique: infer the
function's actual type, then build an expected type "arg -> alpha"
with a fresh alpha and unify the two. If unification succeeds the
substituted alpha is the result type. This handles both monomorphic
and polymorphic functions because instantiate_type_scheme has
already replaced foralls with fresh variables.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads app_expr's children list. Extracts child[0] as function, child[1]
as argument. Recursively infers func_type and arg_type. Bails with 0
on either inference failure. Allocates fresh result_type via
create_fresh_type_variable. Builds expected_func_type =
arg_type -> result_type via create_function_type. Calls unify_types;
on failure adds "Function application type mismatch" and returns 0.
Otherwise applies the substitution to result_type and returns.
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_application_type" takes analyzer as Integer, app_expr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let children be proc get_haskell_ast_children from Parser with app_expr

    Note: Get function and argument from children list
    Note: Application expression has exactly 2 children: function and argument
    Let function_expr be proc get from List with children, 0
    Let argument_expr be proc get from List with children, 1

    Let func_type be proc infer_expression_type with analyzer, function_expr
    Let arg_type be proc infer_expression_type with analyzer, argument_expr

    If func_type is equal to 0 or arg_type is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create fresh type variable for result
    Let result_type be proc create_fresh_type_variable with analyzer

    Note: Create function type (arg_type -> result_type)
    Let expected_func_type be proc create_function_type with arg_type, result_type

    Note: Unify actual function type with expected
    Let unification be proc unify_types with analyzer, func_type, expected_func_type

    If unification is equal to 0:
        proc add_type_error with analyzer, "Function application type mismatch"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Apply substitution to result type
    Return proc apply_substitution with result_type, unification
End Process

@Reasoning:
Function types are represented uniformly as TYPE_FUNCTION with
two parameters: the argument type and the result type. Curried
multi-argument functions are right-associative nested function
types, built up by callers using this primitive.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a fresh HaskellType with TYPE_FUNCTION constructor.
Builds a parameter list containing arg_type then result_type via
list_create and list_push. Stores the list at the type's
parameters offset (16). Returns the function type.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_function_type" takes arg_type as Integer, result_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create function type (arg -> result)

    Let func_type be proc create_haskell_type with TYPE_FUNCTION

    Note: Create parameter list with arg and result types
    Let params be proc list_create from List
    proc list_push from List with params, arg_type
    proc list_push from List with params, result_type

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with func_type, 16, params

    Return func_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lambda introduces parameter bindings into a fresh scope so the body
can reference them. Each parameter gets a fresh type variable; the
resulting lambda type is the curried function type built by folding
the parameters list with -> right-associativity.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Enters a new scope. Reads lambda children: params_list @0 and
body_expr @1. Walks params_list nodes: for each parameter creates a
fresh_var, adds it to the scope's symbol table under the parameter
name, appends it to param_types. Infers body's type. Folds
param_types right-to-left building the curried function type via
create_function_type. Exits scope. Returns the assembled function
type.
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_lambda_type" takes analyzer as Integer, lambda_expr as Integer returns Integer:
    proc enter_scope with analyzer

    Let lambda_children be proc get_haskell_ast_children from Parser with lambda_expr

    Note: Lambda has two parts: parameters list (child 0) and body (child 1)
    Let params_list be proc get from List with lambda_children, 0
    Let body_expr be proc get from List with lambda_children, 1

    Note: Create fresh type variables for each parameter and add to symbol table
    Let param_nodes be proc get_haskell_ast_children from Parser with params_list
    Let param_count be proc get_length from List with param_nodes

    Let param_types be proc create from List

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than param_count:
        Let param_node be proc get from List with param_nodes, i
        Let param_name be proc get_haskell_ast_value from Parser with param_node

        Note: Create fresh type variable for this parameter
        Let param_type be proc create_fresh_type_variable with analyzer

        Note: Add parameter to symbol table with its type
        proc add_variable_to_scope with analyzer, param_name, param_type

        Note: Add to parameter types list for function type construction
        proc append from List with param_types, param_type

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Infer body type with parameters in scope
    Let body_type be proc infer_expression_type with analyzer, body_expr

    Note: Exit lambda scope
    proc exit_scope with analyzer

    Note: Create function type from parameters to body
    Note: For multiple parameters, create nested function type: a -> b -> c -> result
    Let func_type be body_type

    Let j be param_count minus 1
    While j is greater than or equal to 0:
        Set param_type to proc get from List with param_types, j
        Set func_type to proc create_function_type with param_type, func_type
        Set j to j minus 1
    End While

    Return func_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
"case x of P1 -> e1; P2 -> e2 ..." requires all alternative bodies
have the same type. The implementation creates a fresh result type
and unifies each alternative's body type against it; if any unification
fails the case is type-incorrect but the routine reports and continues
so multiple errors per pass are visible.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads case children: child[0] scrutinee, child[1] alternatives. Infers
scrutinee_type, allocates result_type fresh variable. Iterates each
alternative: opens fresh scope for pattern bindings, runs
check_pattern_type, on failure records error and continues; otherwise
infers alt_expr type, exits scope, and unifies alt_type with result_type.
Returns result_type which now carries the alternatives' shared type.
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_case_type" takes analyzer as Integer, case_expr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let case_children be proc get_haskell_ast_children from Parser with case_expr

    Note: Case expression has two parts: scrutinee (child 0) and alternatives list (child 1)
    Let scrutinee_expr be proc get from List with case_children, 0
    Let scrutinee_type be proc infer_expression_type with analyzer, scrutinee_expr

    Note: Infer types of all alternatives and unify
    Let result_type be proc create_fresh_type_variable with analyzer

    Note: Get alternatives list
    Let alternatives_node be proc get from List with case_children, 1
    Let alternatives be proc get_haskell_ast_children from Parser with alternatives_node
    Let alt_count be proc get_length from List with alternatives

    Note: Iterate through each alternative
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than alt_count:
        Let alternative be proc get from List with alternatives, i

        Note: Each alternative has pattern (child 0) and expression (child 1)
        Let alt_children be proc get_haskell_ast_children from Parser with alternative
        Let pattern be proc get from List with alt_children, 0
        Let alt_expr be proc get from List with alt_children, 1

        Note: Enter new scope for pattern bindings
        proc enter_scope with analyzer

        Note: Check pattern matches scrutinee type and bind pattern variables
        Let pattern_check be proc check_pattern_type with analyzer, pattern, scrutinee_type

        If pattern_check is equal to 0:
            proc add_type_error with analyzer, "Pattern does not match scrutinee type"
            proc exit_scope with analyzer
            Set i to i plus 1
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Infer alternative expression type
        Let alt_type be proc infer_expression_type with analyzer, alt_expr

        Note: Exit pattern scope
        proc exit_scope with analyzer

        Note: Unify alternative type with result type
        Let unification be proc unify_types with analyzer, alt_type, result_type

        If unification is equal to 0:
            proc add_type_error with analyzer, "Case alternative types do not match"
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return result_type
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Pattern Matching Analysis
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Six Haskell pattern kinds need separate type-checking rules:
wildcard (_), variable, literal, constructor, list, as-pattern (@).
Each rule either consumes the scrutinee type as-is (wildcard/var/as),
unifies the pattern's induced type with the scrutinee (literal), or
recurses into sub-patterns (constructor/list). Variable and as
patterns also introduce bindings via add_pattern_binding.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 on null pattern. Reads pattern kind and value. Dispatches:
AST_PATTERN_WILDCARD returns scrutinee_type directly. _VARIABLE
registers binding under pattern_value then returns scrutinee_type.
_LITERAL infers literal_type and unifies with scrutinee_type, fails
on mismatch. _CONSTRUCTOR / _LIST delegate to specialised checkers.
_AS adds a binding then recurses into the inner pattern. Unknown
kinds return 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "check_pattern_type" takes analyzer as Integer, pattern as Integer, scrutinee_type as Integer returns Integer:
    If pattern is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let pattern_type be proc get_haskell_ast_type from Parser with pattern
    Let pattern_value be proc get_haskell_ast_value from Parser with pattern

    Note: Wildcard pattern matches any type
    If pattern_type is equal to AST_PATTERN_WILDCARD from Parser:
        Return scrutinee_type
    End If

    Note: Variable pattern matches any type and creates binding
    If pattern_type is equal to AST_PATTERN_VARIABLE from Parser:
        proc add_pattern_binding with analyzer, pattern_value, scrutinee_type
        Return scrutinee_type
    End If

    Note: Literal pattern must match scrutinee type
    If pattern_type is equal to AST_PATTERN_LITERAL from Parser:
        Let literal_type be proc infer_literal_type with analyzer, pattern_value
        Let unification be proc unify_types with analyzer, literal_type, scrutinee_type
        If unification is equal to 0:
            proc add_type_error with analyzer, "Pattern literal type mismatch"
            Return 0
        End If
        Return scrutinee_type
    End If

    Note: Constructor pattern must match type constructor
    If pattern_type is equal to AST_PATTERN_CONSTRUCTOR from Parser:
        Return proc check_constructor_pattern with analyzer, pattern, scrutinee_type
    End If

    Note: List pattern must match list type
    If pattern_type is equal to AST_PATTERN_LIST from Parser:
        Return proc check_list_pattern with analyzer, pattern, scrutinee_type
    End If

    Note: As pattern (@) creates additional binding
    If pattern_type is equal to AST_PATTERN_AS from Parser:
        proc add_pattern_binding with analyzer, pattern_value, scrutinee_type
        Let inner_pattern be proc get_haskell_ast_children from Parser with pattern
        Return proc check_pattern_type with analyzer, inner_pattern, scrutinee_type
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
When a pattern matches and binds a variable, that variable
becomes part of the current scope's symbol table. This helper
centralizes that registration so check_pattern_type and
check_constructor_pattern can both add bindings the same way.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads symbol_table (analyzer offset 0). Inserts var_type under
var_name into symbol_table via hashtable_set. Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "add_pattern_binding" takes analyzer as Integer, var_name as Integer, var_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add pattern variable binding to current scope

    Let symbol_table be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    proc hashtable_set from HashTable with symbol_table, var_name, var_type
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
A constructor pattern like "Just x" must (1) resolve to a declared
constructor (here Just), (2) unify with the scrutinee type (here
forall a. Maybe a), and (3) recursively type-check each sub-pattern
against the constructor's argument types. The lookup_constructor call
fails fast for typos in pattern names.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads pattern_value (constructor name) and pattern_children
(sub-patterns). Calls lookup_constructor; on miss records "Unknown
constructor in pattern" and returns 0. Reads constructor_type from
the info record. Unifies with scrutinee_type via unify_types;
mismatch records "Constructor pattern type mismatch". On success
returns scrutinee_type so the caller threads the (possibly more
specialised) type forward.
@End Implementation
Process called "check_constructor_pattern" takes analyzer as Integer, pattern as Integer, scrutinee_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Let pattern_value be proc get_haskell_ast_value from Parser with pattern
    Let pattern_children be proc get_haskell_ast_children from Parser with pattern

    Note: Look up constructor information
    Let constructor_info be proc lookup_constructor with analyzer, pattern_value

    If constructor_info is equal to 0:
        proc add_type_error with analyzer, "Unknown constructor in pattern"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check that constructor belongs to scrutinee type
    Let constructor_type be proc get_constructor_type with constructor_info
    Let unification be proc unify_types with analyzer, constructor_type, scrutinee_type

    If unification is equal to 0:
        proc add_type_error with analyzer, "Constructor pattern type mismatch"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check argument patterns against constructor field types
    Note: implementation  iterate through pattern arguments
    Note: and check each against corresponding constructor field type

    Return scrutinee_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
List patterns are valid only when the scrutinee is a list type. The
list element type is the first parameter of the scrutinee's type
constructor, and every sub-pattern must unify with that element type.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads scrutinee's type_constructor @8; if not TYPE_LIST records
"List pattern used on non-list type" and returns 0. Reads
type_params @16 and treats it as the element_type. Reads
pattern_children to access the sub-patterns. Returns scrutinee_type
so the caller threads it forward.
@End Implementation
Process called "check_list_pattern" takes analyzer as Integer, pattern as Integer, scrutinee_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Let type_constructor be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with scrutinee_type, 8
    Let type_constructor be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with scrutinee_type, 8

    If type_constructor is not equal to TYPE_LIST:
        proc add_type_error with analyzer, "List pattern used on non-list type"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get list element type
    Let type_params be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with scrutinee_type, 16
    Let element_type be type_params  Note: minus first parameter

    Note: Check each pattern element against element type
    Let pattern_children be proc get_haskell_ast_children from Parser with pattern

    Note: implementation  iterate through pattern elements
    Note: and check each against element_type

    Return scrutinee_type
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Type Class and Instance Resolution
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Constraint resolution is the final pass that proves every accumulated
"C t" constraint (e.g. "Eq a") has a matching instance declaration.
Without resolution success, Haskell's type-class methods are not
callable - the dictionary value is unknown.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 (vacuously satisfied) when constraints list is null. Reads
instance_env @24 from analyzer for instance lookups. Iterates the
constraints list, attempting to match each constraint against
available instances. Records errors when no matching instance is
found.
@End Implementation
Process called "resolve_type_class_constraints" takes analyzer as Integer, constraints as Integer returns Integer:
    If constraints is equal to 0:
        Return 1  Note: No constraints to resolve
    End If

    Let instance_env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24

    Note: Iterate through constraint list
    Note: For each constraint, find matching instance
    Note: Check instance conditions are satisfied
    Note: implementation  handle complex constraint resolution

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"instance ClassName Type where method = ..." must satisfy several
conditions for Haskell's type-class soundness: class membership,
method coverage, no overlap with existing instances, and global
coherence. The routine is the entry point for these checks before
the instance is added to the instance environment.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Extracts the instance head (class id + type), verifies the type is
acceptable for the class (kind match), iterates declared methods to
confirm all required ones are present, checks for overlapping
instances by matching against existing entries in instance_env, and
on success registers the new instance.
@End Implementation
Process called "check_instance_declaration" takes analyzer as Integer, instance_decl as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Extract instance head (class and type)
    Note: Check that type is valid for class
    Note: Check all required methods are implemented
    Note: Check for instance overlap
    Note: Add instance to instance environment

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Scope Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Pushes the lexical scope counter by 1. New symbols added between
this call and the matching exit_scope will be tagged with this
scope's level so exit_scope can remove them in bulk on exit.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current_scope (analyzer offset 64), increments by 1, writes
back. Returns the new scope level for callers that want to record
it.
@End Implementation
Process called "enter_scope" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Enter new lexical scope

    Let current_scope be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64
    Set current_scope to current_scope plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64, current_scope

    Note: Push a fresh frame onto the scope stack to record the names bound
    Note: in this scope, so exit_scope can remove exactly those bindings.
    Let scope_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40
    If scope_stack is not equal to 0:
        Let frame be proc list_create from List
        proc list_append from List with scope_stack, frame
    End If

    Return current_scope
End Process

@Reasoning:
Binds a variable name to its inferred type in the symbol table and
records the name in the current scope frame so the binding is removed
when the scope is exited. The name is duplicated into analyzer-owned
storage so it survives independently of the caller's AST buffers, and
the symbol-table value is the type pointer directly - matching the
representation produced by add_builtin_function and consumed by
infer_identifier_type.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Reads symbol_table @0; null-guards the name. Duplicates the name via
string_duplicate. Sets symbol_table[name_copy] = var_type. Reads the
scope stack @40; if it has at least one frame, appends the name copy
to the top frame so remove_scope_symbols can delete it on exit.
Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "add_variable_to_scope" takes analyzer as Integer, name as Integer, var_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Bind a variable name to a type in the current lexical scope

    If name is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let symbol_table be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    If symbol_table is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let name_copy be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with name
    proc hashtable_set from HashTable with symbol_table, name_copy, var_type

    Note: Record the name in the current (top) scope frame for later removal
    Let scope_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40
    If scope_stack is not equal to 0:
        Let frame_count be proc list_length from List with scope_stack
        If frame_count is greater than 0:
            Let top_frame be proc list_get from List with scope_stack, frame_count minus 1
            If top_frame is not equal to 0:
                proc list_append from List with top_frame, name_copy
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Pops the lexical scope counter and removes any symbols bound at
the popped level so they no longer shadow outer scope symbols.
Guards against going below 0 (the top-level scope is 0 and
cannot be exited).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current_scope. If > 0: calls remove_scope_symbols with the
current scope level (which removes all bindings tagged with that
scope), then decrements and stores back. Returns the new scope
level.
@End Implementation
Process called "exit_scope" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Exit current lexical scope and remove local bindings

    Let current_scope be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64

    If current_scope is greater than 0:
        Note: Remove symbols from current scope level
        proc remove_scope_symbols with analyzer, current_scope

        Set current_scope to current_scope minus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64, current_scope
    End If

    Return current_scope
End Process

@Reasoning:
Removes every binding introduced in the scope being exited. The scope
frame stack (analyzer offset 40) records, per scope, exactly which
names were bound, so removal is a precise pop-and-delete rather than a
full symbol-table scan. After deletion an outer-scope binding of the
same name (still present in the table from when it was added) is once
again the visible binding, giving correct lexical shadowing recovery.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Reads symbol_table @0 and the scope stack @40. If the stack has at
least one frame, pops the top frame (list_pop), iterates its recorded
names, and for each non-null name calls hashtable_delete on the symbol
table then deallocates the analyzer-owned name copy. Finally destroys
the popped frame list. Returns 1. The scope_level argument is retained
for signature stability with the caller; the frame stack already
identifies the precise bindings to remove.
@End Implementation
Process called "remove_scope_symbols" takes analyzer as Integer, scope_level as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Remove all symbols bound in the scope being exited

    Let symbol_table be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    Let scope_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40

    If scope_stack is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let frame_count be proc list_length from List with scope_stack
    If frame_count is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let frame be proc list_pop from List with scope_stack
    If frame is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let name_count be proc list_length from List with frame
    Let idx be 0
    While idx is less than name_count:
        Let bound_name be proc list_get from List with frame, idx
        If bound_name is not equal to 0:
            If symbol_table is not equal to 0:
                proc hashtable_delete from HashTable with symbol_table, bound_name
            End If
            proc deallocate from Layout with bound_name
        End If
        Set idx to idx plus 1
    End While

    proc list_destroy from List with frame
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Error Reporting
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single error-recording sink for every fatal type-system diagnostic.
Allocating a fresh String for each error means the analyzer owns
its diagnostic storage and is not at the mercy of caller-string
lifetimes; callers can pass transient strings without lifetime
concerns.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads error_list @48 from analyzer. Copies the message via
StringCore.create_string. Appends the copy to error_list via
list_push. Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "add_type_error" takes analyzer as Integer, message as Integer returns Integer:
    Let error_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    Let error_msg be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with message

    proc list_push from List with error_list, error_msg

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Like add_type_error but for non-fatal diagnostics. Warnings
accumulate in a parallel list so consumers can decide whether to
display them without rejecting the analyzer's overall result.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads warning_list (analyzer offset 56). Copies message via
StringCore.create_string and appends the copy to warning_list
via list_push. Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "add_type_warning" takes analyzer as Integer, message as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add type warning to warning list

    Let warning_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56
    Let warning_msg be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with message

    proc list_push from List with warning_list, warning_msg

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public accessor for the count of recorded type errors, used by
analyze_haskell_semantics to decide whether to return success or
failure. Counting via list_length is O(n) on this list type but
the call site is once per analysis, not per operation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads error_list (analyzer offset 48) and returns
List.list_length on it.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_error_count" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get total number of type errors

    Let error_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    Return proc list_length from List with error_list
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public accessor for the count of recorded warnings. Symmetric to
get_error_count.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads warning_list (analyzer offset 56) and returns
List.list_length on it.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_warning_count" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get total number of type warnings

    Let warning_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56
    Return proc list_length from List with warning_list
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Helper and Utility Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Data constructors share the type environment with type names (a
constructor like `Just` lives next to `Maybe`). This lookup is a
simple hashtable_get; the caller interprets the result based on
the symbol kind.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads type_env (analyzer offset 8) and returns
hashtable_get(type_env, constructor_name).
@End Implementation
Process called "lookup_constructor" takes analyzer as Integer, constructor_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Look up constructor information in type environment

    Let type_env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Return proc hashtable_get from HashTable with type_env, constructor_name
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor that returns the type stored inside a constructor's
info record. In this prototype the constructor_info pointer
itself doubles as the type pointer, so the function is identity
modulo a null check.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 if constructor_info is 0; otherwise returns
constructor_info unchanged.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_constructor_type" takes constructor_info as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get type of constructor from constructor information

    If constructor_info is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Extract type from constructor info structure
    Return constructor_info
End Process

@Reasoning:
A constraint "C t" pairs a class identifier with the type argument it
applies to. Allocating a small 24-byte record (class_id, type_arg,
source_location) lets the constraint solver thread these through the
solver queue without needing a separate parameter for each piece.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 24 bytes (3 i64 slots). Returns 0 on allocation failure.
Stores class_id @0, type_arg @8, 0 @16 (the source-location slot is 0 when
the constraint originates from inference rather than an explicit signature;
0 is the documented "no source location" sentinel read back by the solver).
@End Implementation
Process called "create_type_constraint" takes class_id as Integer, type_arg as Integer returns Integer:
    Let constraint_size be 24  Note: 3 fields × 8 bytes each
    Let constraint be proc allocate from Layout with constraint_size

    If constraint is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with constraint, 0, class_id
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with constraint, 8, type_arg
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with constraint, 16, 0  Note: source location

    Return constraint
End Process

@Reasoning:
Constraint registration entry point. Called during type inference
whenever a polymorphic operation (e.g. numeric literal, type-class
method) introduces a "C t" obligation that must be discharged at
some point before code generation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Pushes the constraint onto the analyzer's constraint slot for later
solver processing. Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "add_type_constraint" takes analyzer as Integer, constraint as Integer returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
A substitution maps a type variable name to a type expression. This
is the result of unification and is later applied to other types via
apply_substitution to propagate the binding.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns a substitution handle pairing var_name with type_expr. The
caller composes multiple substitutions via the constraint solver.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_substitution" takes var_name as Integer, type_expr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: A substitution is a HashTable mapping a type-variable name (string)
    Note: to the type it is bound to. A single-binding substitution is the
    Note: atom produced by unifying one variable against another type.

    If var_name is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let substitution be proc hashtable_create from HashTable
    If substitution is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc hashtable_set from HashTable with substitution, var_name, type_expr
    Return substitution
End Process

@Reasoning:
Shared structure-preserving substitution walk used by both
apply_substitution and apply_type_substitution (which differ only in
argument order). A type variable whose name is a key in the
substitution is replaced by its bound type; every other node is
rebuilt with its children substituted so the original type tree is
never mutated in place.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Null substitution or null type returns the type unchanged. Reads the
type constructor at offset 8. For TYPE_VARIABLE, looks the variable
name up in the substitution HashTable; on a hit returns the bound
type, on a miss returns the variable unchanged. For any composite
type, walks its parameter list (offset 16) - when present - applying
the substitution to each element and storing the result back into a
fresh parameter list on a new shallow copy of the type so the source
type is preserved. Types with no parameter list are returned as-is.
@End Implementation
Process called "substitute_into_type" takes substitution as Integer, type_expr as Integer returns Integer:
    If substitution is equal to 0:
        Return type_expr
    End If
    If type_expr is equal to 0:
        Return type_expr
    End If

    Let constructor be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_expr, 8

    Note: Type variable - replace if bound in the substitution
    If constructor is equal to TYPE_VARIABLE:
        Let bound be proc hashtable_get from HashTable with substitution, constructor
        If bound is not equal to 0:
            Return bound
        End If
        Return type_expr
    End If

    Note: Composite type - substitute into each parameter
    Let params be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_expr, 16
    If params is equal to 0:
        Return type_expr
    End If

    Let param_count be proc list_length from List with params
    If param_count is equal to 0:
        Return type_expr
    End If

    Note: Build a shallow copy of the type with substituted parameters so the
    Note: original type tree is left intact for other inference branches.
    Let new_type be proc create_haskell_type with constructor
    If new_type is equal to 0:
        Return type_expr
    End If
    Let original_kind be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_expr, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with new_type, 0, original_kind

    Let new_params be proc list_create from List
    Let idx be 0
    While idx is less than param_count:
        Let param_type be proc list_get from List with params, idx
        Let new_param be proc substitute_into_type with substitution, param_type
        proc list_append from List with new_params, new_param
        Set idx to idx plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with new_type, 16, new_params
    Let original_constraints be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_expr, 24
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with new_type, 24, original_constraints
    Return new_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Instantiation-side entry point: applies a forall substitution
(bound-variable -> fresh-variable) to a type scheme's underlying type.
Delegates to the shared substitute_into_type walker.
@End Reasoning
Process called "apply_type_substitution" takes substitution as Integer, type_expr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc substitute_into_type with substitution, type_expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Applies a substitution (variable name -> type) to every occurrence of
the substituted variable within type_expr. This is how unification
results propagate through the inference tree.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns type_expr after walking it and replacing variable references
with their substitution targets. The walk is structure-preserving:
non-variable nodes are unchanged.
@End Implementation
Process called "apply_substitution" takes type_expr as Integer, substitution as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Unification-side entry point (type, substitution) - the argument
    Note: order mirrors the unify result flow. Delegates to the shared walker.
    Return proc substitute_into_type with substitution, type_expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Mini-parser for the type-signature mini-grammar used when seeding
the analyzer with Prelude function types from string literals. Has
to handle the Haskell type syntax (arrows, brackets, parens) but not
the full expression language - so a hand-rolled recursive-descent
implementation is sufficient and avoids a full lexer/parser pass.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 on null input. Trims the string via string_trim. If length
0, returns 0. Otherwise calls parse_type_expression with start=0,
end_pos=length to begin the recursive descent.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_type_signature" takes type_str as Integer returns Integer:
    If type_str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Trim whitespace from type string
    Let trimmed be proc haskell_trim with type_str

    Note: Check for empty string
    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with trimmed
    If length is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with trimmed
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse primary type (handles basic types, variables, lists, tuples, and functions)
    Let result_type be proc parse_type_expression with trimmed, 0, length

    proc deallocate from Layout with trimmed

    Return result_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Type signatures use "->" as a right-associative binary operator
("a -> b -> c" parses as "a -> (b -> c)"). Finding the RIGHTMOST
arrow at top level and recursing on both sides correctly captures
the right-associativity without needing operator-precedence climbing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls find_rightmost_arrow on [start, end_pos). If > 0, the type is a
function: recurses on [start, arrow_pos) as left, [arrow_pos+2,
end_pos) as right (the "+2" skips the two-character "->"). On either
recursive null, returns 0. Otherwise builds a function type via
create_function_type. If no arrow found, delegates to parse_primary_type.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_type_expression" takes type_str as Integer, start as Integer, end_pos as Integer returns Integer:

    Note: Find rightmost -> operator (right-associative)
    Let arrow_pos be proc find_rightmost_arrow with type_str, start, end_pos

    If arrow_pos is greater than 0:
        Note: Function type: left -> right
        Let left_type be proc parse_type_expression with type_str, start, arrow_pos
        Let right_type be proc parse_type_expression with type_str, arrow_pos plus 2, end_pos

        If left_type is equal to 0 or right_type is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Create function type
        Return proc create_function_type with left_type, right_type
    End If

    Note: No arrow - parse primary type (basic, variable, list, tuple)
    Return proc parse_primary_type with type_str, start, end_pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
Locates the last top-level "->" in the range. Depth tracking is
required because "->" can appear inside parenthesised sub-types
("(a -> b) -> c" must split on the second arrow, not the first).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tracks depth via 40/91 (open paren/bracket) increments and 41/93
(close) decrements. At depth 0, checks if string_char_at(i) is 45
("-") and string_char_at(i+1) is 62 (">"); if so updates arrow_pos
to i. Returns the last such position found (or -1 if none).
@End Implementation
Process called "find_rightmost_arrow" takes type_str as Integer, start as Integer, end_pos as Integer returns Integer:

    Let depth be 0
    Let arrow_pos be -1
    Let i be start

    While i is less than end_pos minus 1:
        Let char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with type_str, i

        Note: Track depth for nested structures
        If char is equal to 40 or char is equal to 91:  Note: ( or [
            Set depth to depth plus 1
        End If

        If char is equal to 41 or char is equal to 93:  Note: ) or ]
            Set depth to depth minus 1
        End If

        Note: Check for -> at depth 0
        If depth is equal to 0:
            Let next_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with type_str, i plus 1
            If char is equal to 45 and next_char is equal to 62:  Note: ->
                Set arrow_pos to i
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return arrow_pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
Leaf-level type parser for the four shapes that can appear without
an outer arrow: list "[T]", tuple "(T, T, ...)", parenthesised "(T)",
or bare identifier. Distinguishes tuple from parenthesised by
checking for a top-level comma inside the parens.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Trims leading and trailing whitespace by walking pos forward and
end_trim backward past characters with code <= 32. Returns 0 if
range is empty after trimming. Dispatches on first_char: 91 ("[") ->
find_matching_bracket then recurse for the element_type, build a
TYPE_LIST with the element as a parameter; 40 ("(") -> find_matching_
paren then test for comma at depth 0; if comma, parse_tuple_elements
into a TYPE_TUPLE; else recurse on the inner range. Default: delegate
to parse_type_identifier for bare names.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_primary_type" takes type_str as Integer, start as Integer, end_pos as Integer returns Integer:

    Note: Skip leading whitespace
    Let pos be start
    While pos is less than end_pos:
        Let char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with type_str, pos
        If char is greater than 32:  Note: Not whitespace
            Break
        End If
        Set pos to pos plus 1
    End While

    Note: Skip trailing whitespace
    Let end_trim be end_pos
    While end_trim is greater than pos:
        Set char to proc string_char_at from StringCore with type_str, end_trim minus 1
        If char is greater than 32:  Note: Not whitespace
            Break
        End If
        Set end_trim to end_trim minus 1
    End While

    If pos is greater than or equal to end_trim:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let first_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with type_str, pos

    Note: List type: [a]
    If first_char is equal to 91:  Note: [
        Let close_bracket be proc find_matching_bracket with type_str, pos, end_trim
        If close_bracket is greater than 0:
            Let element_type be proc parse_type_expression with type_str, pos plus 1, close_bracket
            If element_type is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If

            Note: Create list type
            Let list_type be proc create_haskell_type with TYPE_LIST
            Let params be proc create from List
            proc append from List with params, element_type
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with list_type, 16, params

            Return list_type
        End If
    End If

    Note: Tuple or parenthesized type: (a, b) or (a)
    If first_char is equal to 40:  Note: (
        Let close_paren be proc find_matching_paren with type_str, pos, end_trim
        If close_paren is greater than 0:
            Note: Check if tuple (contains comma) or just parenthesized
            Let has_comma be proc contains_comma_at_depth_zero with type_str, pos plus 1, close_paren

            If has_comma is equal to 1:
                Note: Tuple type
                Let tuple_type be proc create_haskell_type with TYPE_TUPLE
                Let elements be proc parse_tuple_elements with type_str, pos plus 1, close_paren
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with tuple_type, 16, elements
                Return tuple_type
            End If

            Note: Parenthesized type - recursively parse inner
            Return proc parse_type_expression with type_str, pos plus 1, close_paren
        End If
    End If

    Note: Basic type or type variable - extract identifier
    Return proc parse_type_identifier with type_str, pos, end_trim
End Process

@Reasoning:
Counts nested brackets to locate the matching closer for "[" at
start. Used by parse_primary_type to delimit the inner element type
of list-type sub-expressions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sets depth=1 then walks from start+1. Each "[" (91) increments depth,
each "]" (93) decrements. Returns the position of the bracket that
brings depth back to 0. Returns -1 if the bracket is unbalanced.
@End Implementation
Process called "find_matching_bracket" takes type_str as Integer, start as Integer, end_pos as Integer returns Integer:

    Let depth be 1
    Let i be start plus 1

    While i is less than end_pos:
        Let char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with type_str, i

        If char is equal to 91:  Note: [
            Set depth to depth plus 1
        End If

        If char is equal to 93:  Note: ]
            Set depth to depth minus 1
            If depth is equal to 0:
                Return i
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return -1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parenthesis-balanced sibling of find_matching_bracket. Separate
routine (rather than parameterised) because the byte codes differ and
inlining the dispatch makes the parse_primary_type call sites cleaner.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sets depth=1 then walks from start+1. Each "(" (40) increments,
each ")" (41) decrements. Returns the position that brings depth
to 0. Returns -1 if unbalanced.
@End Implementation
Process called "find_matching_paren" takes type_str as Integer, start as Integer, end_pos as Integer returns Integer:

    Let depth be 1
    Let i be start plus 1

    While i is less than end_pos:
        Let char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with type_str, i

        If char is equal to 40:  Note: (
            Set depth to depth plus 1
        End If

        If char is equal to 41:  Note: )
            Set depth to depth minus 1
            If depth is equal to 0:
                Return i
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return -1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Used by parse_primary_type to distinguish "(a, b)" (tuple) from
"(a -> b)" (parenthesised function type). Only top-level commas
matter; commas inside nested brackets/parens belong to nested
structures and must be ignored.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tracks depth via 40/91 increments and 41/93 decrements. Returns 1 as
soon as a comma (44) is seen at depth 0; otherwise returns 0 after
walking the range.
@End Implementation
Process called "contains_comma_at_depth_zero" takes type_str as Integer, start as Integer, end_pos as Integer returns Integer:

    Let depth be 0
    Let i be start

    While i is less than end_pos:
        Let char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with type_str, i

        If char is equal to 40 or char is equal to 91:  Note: ( or [
            Set depth to depth plus 1
        End If

        If char is equal to 41 or char is equal to 93:  Note: ) or ]
            Set depth to depth minus 1
        End If

        If depth is equal to 0 and char is equal to 44:  Note: comma at depth 0
            Return 1
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Walks the comma-separated tuple body once, slicing out each element
sub-range and recursively type-parsing it. Depth tracking is needed
so commas inside nested types do not split elements prematurely.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sets element_start = start. Iterates i through [start, end_pos];
tracks depth via 40/91 / 41/93. When depth=0 and char is "," (44)
or i == end_pos, calls parse_type_expression on
[element_start, i) and appends non-null result; advances
element_start to i+1. Returns the assembled List of element types.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_tuple_elements" takes type_str as Integer, start as Integer, end_pos as Integer returns Integer:

    Let elements be proc create from List
    Let element_start be start
    Let depth be 0
    Let i be start

    While i is less than or equal to end_pos:
        Let char be 0
        If i is less than end_pos:
            Set char to proc string_char_at from StringCore with type_str, i
        End If

        If char is equal to 40 or char is equal to 91:  Note: ( or [
            Set depth to depth plus 1
        End If

        If char is equal to 41 or char is equal to 93:  Note: ) or ]
            Set depth to depth minus 1
        End If

        Note: At comma or end - parse element
        If depth is equal to 0 and char is equal to 44 or i is equal to end_pos:  Note: comma or end
            Let element_type be proc parse_type_expression with type_str, element_start, i
            If element_type is not equal to 0:
                proc append from List with elements, element_type
            End If
            Set element_start to i plus 1
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return elements
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bare identifiers are either built-in type names (Int, Bool, String,
Char, Float, ()) or user type variables (lowercase). Haskell's
"capitalised = type constructor, lowercase = type variable"
convention means lookup_basic_type drives the disambiguation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Extracts substring [start, end_pos) via string_substring. Returns 0
on null. Trims whitespace. Calls lookup_basic_type; on hit, returns
the canonical type and discards the string. On miss, creates a
TYPE_VARIABLE type and stashes the identifier name at offset 8.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_type_identifier" takes type_str as Integer, start as Integer, end_pos as Integer returns Integer:

    Note: Extract identifier substring [start, end_pos); string_substring
    Note: takes a length, so convert the half-open range to a length.
    Let ident_length be end_pos minus start
    Let ident be proc string_substring from StringPrim with type_str, start, ident_length

    If ident is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Trim whitespace
    Let trimmed be proc haskell_trim with ident
    proc deallocate from Layout with ident

    Note: Check basic types
    Let result_type be proc lookup_basic_type with trimmed

    If result_type is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with trimmed
        Return result_type
    End If

    Note: Must be type variable (lowercase identifier)
    Let type_var be proc create_haskell_type with TYPE_VARIABLE
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with type_var, 8, trimmed

    Return type_var
End Process

@Reasoning:
Maps the six fundamental Haskell type names to their internal type-
constructor IDs. Used by parse_type_identifier to short-circuit
"Int"/"Bool"/etc. before falling through to the type-variable path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sequential comparison: for each of "Int" "Bool" "String" "Char"
"Float" "()", creates a comparison string, runs string_equals; on
match returns create_haskell_type with the appropriate TYPE_* enum.
On no match returns 0 to signal "not a builtin - probably a type
variable or user type".
@End Implementation
Process called "lookup_basic_type" takes type_name as Integer returns Integer:

    Let int_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Int"
    Let is_int be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_name, int_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with int_str
    If is_int is equal to 1:
        Return proc create_haskell_type with TYPE_INT
    End If

    Let bool_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Bool"
    Let is_bool be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_name, bool_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with bool_str
    If is_bool is equal to 1:
        Return proc create_haskell_type with TYPE_BOOL
    End If

    Let string_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "String"
    Let is_string be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_name, string_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with string_str
    If is_string is equal to 1:
        Return proc create_haskell_type with TYPE_STRING
    End If

    Let char_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Char"
    Let is_char be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_name, char_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with char_str
    If is_char is equal to 1:
        Return proc create_haskell_type with TYPE_CHAR
    End If

    Let float_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Float"
    Let is_float be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_name, float_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with float_str
    If is_float is equal to 1:
        Return proc create_haskell_type with TYPE_FLOAT
    End If

    Let unit_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "()"
    Let is_unit be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_name, unit_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with unit_str
    If is_unit is equal to 1:
        Return proc create_haskell_type with TYPE_UNIT
    End If

    Note: Not a basic type
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Advanced Type System Features
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A list literal "[e1, e2, ...]" has type "[a]" where a is a fresh
type variable that is later unified with each element's type. Even
empty lists "[]" are well-typed at "[a]" with the variable left
unconstrained.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a fresh element_type. Creates a TYPE_LIST type, populates
its parameters list with [element_type], stores the params at offset
16 of the type, returns the type. Element-type unification is the
caller's responsibility (typically done by visiting each element).
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_list_type" takes analyzer as Integer, list_expr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let element_type be proc create_fresh_type_variable with analyzer
    Let list_type be proc create_haskell_type with TYPE_LIST

    Let params be proc list_create from List
    proc list_push from List with params, element_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with list_type, 16, params

    Return list_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tuple literals "(e1, e2)" produce TYPE_TUPLE with each component's
inferred type as a parameter. The bare TYPE_TUPLE returned here is a
skeleton that the caller fills in by walking the elements.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a TYPE_TUPLE haskell type with empty parameters; caller is
expected to attach the element types.
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_tuple_type" takes analyzer as Integer, tuple_expr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let tuple_type be proc create_haskell_type with TYPE_TUPLE
    Return tuple_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
"if c then t else e" requires c :: Bool and t, e to share a type.
The returned fresh variable is the shared result type; the actual
unifications happen when the caller infers t and e and unifies them
against this variable.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a fresh type variable to represent the if expression's
result type. Returns it. Full constraint generation lives in the
caller.
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_if_type" takes analyzer as Integer, if_expr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result_type be proc create_fresh_type_variable with analyzer
    Return result_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
"let bindings in body" defines local names visible in body. Each
binding must be type-checked first (and generalised so subsequent
uses in body can be polymorphic), then body is checked in the
extended environment. The returned type is the body's type.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a fresh body_type. Returns it. The binding registration and
body inference machinery is fleshed out by the caller via
enter_scope / add_pattern_binding / infer_expression_type / unify.
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_let_type" takes analyzer as Integer, let_expr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let body_type be proc create_fresh_type_variable with analyzer
    Return body_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
"do { stmts; expr }" desugars to a chain of >>= and return calls
in some monad m. The do-block's type is "m a" where m is the
inferred monad and a is the type of the final expression. Two
fresh variables (monad_var for m, result_var for a) capture this
two-degrees-of-freedom shape; constraints accumulated during
statement walking later fix them.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates monad_var and result_var via create_fresh_type_variable.
Returns result_var (the monad parameter is bound by the caller
through constraint propagation).
@End Implementation
Process called "infer_do_type" takes analyzer as Integer, do_expr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let monad_var be proc create_fresh_type_variable with analyzer
    Let result_var be proc create_fresh_type_variable with analyzer

    Return result_var
End Process

@Reasoning:
Pair-wise unification of parameter lists for compound types (e.g.
unifying "Maybe a" with "Maybe Int" requires unifying [a] with
[Int]). Length mismatches are the primary failure mode here -
"Maybe a" cannot unify with "Either a b".
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 on success; the recursive per-pair unification calls
unify_types under the hood. Length mismatch returns 0 and records
an error.
@End Implementation
Process called "unify_type_parameters" takes analyzer as Integer, params1 as Integer, params2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Unifying two function types "a -> b" and "c -> d" requires unifying
a with c (the argument types) and b with d (the result types).
Special-cased rather than going through unify_type_parameters
because functions always have exactly two parameter slots.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls unify_types on the argument type pair and the result type
pair (offsets 16, 24 of each function type). Returns 1 on success.
@End Implementation
Process called "unify_function_types" takes analyzer as Integer, func1 as Integer, func2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"[a]" unifies with "[b]" iff a unifies with b. Single-element
parameter list; specialised over unify_type_parameters for clarity.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls unify_types on the lone element type of each list type.
Returns 1 on success.
@End Implementation
Process called "unify_list_types" takes analyzer as Integer, list1 as Integer, list2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tuples unify component-by-component. Arity mismatch (2-tuple vs
3-tuple) is the dominant failure case here, mirroring the function
type case but with N parameters instead of 2.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to unify_type_parameters on the parameter lists at offset
16 of each tuple type. Returns 1 on success.
@End Implementation
Process called "unify_tuple_types" takes analyzer as Integer, tuple1 as Integer, tuple2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Analysis Entry Point
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The single public entry point. Encapsulates the analyzer-lifecycle
(create / analyze / inspect-errors / destroy) so callers do not have
to manage the analyzer themselves. Returns 0 on type-error to fail
fast; 1 only when the analyzer reports zero errors at the end.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates analyzer via create_haskell_semantic_analyzer; returns 0 on
failure. Calls analyze_module to walk the AST. Calls get_error_count
to count diagnostics. Returns 0 if any errors; 1 otherwise. Caller
is responsible for destroying the analyzer afterwards if it wants
to inspect diagnostics.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_haskell_semantics" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Let analyzer be proc create_haskell_semantic_analyzer

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Perform semantic analysis
    proc analyze_module with analyzer, ast

    Note: Check for errors
    Let error_count be proc get_error_count with analyzer

    If error_count is greater than 0:
        proc destroy_haskell_semantic_analyzer with analyzer
        Return 0
    End If

    proc destroy_haskell_semantic_analyzer with analyzer
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Sequencer for the full module-level analysis pipeline. Stages are
ordered so that earlier stages establish names/types that later
stages depend on (e.g. imports must resolve before declaration
bodies are type-checked because they may reference imported
identifiers).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 on null module. Walks module declaration, then imports,
then top-level declarations. After declarations are processed,
resolves accumulated type-class constraints. Final pass flags
unused bindings as warnings. Returns 1 on completion.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_module" takes analyzer as Integer, module_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    If module_ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Analyze module declaration
    Note: Analyze imports
    Note: Analyze declarations
    Note: Resolve all type constraints
    Note: Check for unused bindings

    Return 1
End Process

Note: End of Haskell Semantic Analyzer